Patch: aurora lib/gx/command_processor.cpp -- unaligned_load takes const void*
Applies to: Aurora repo itself (external_refs/repos/aurora), commit 1dde08f.
Tracked file, edited directly (not a FetchContent dependency).

Why:
The zig-cc (x86_64-windows-gnu, LLVM-backed) build of the `simple` example
ran the full Aurora init sequence (WebGPU instance, D3D12 adapter/device,
surface, pipeline cache) successfully, opened a real window, then hard
crashed on the very first frame with:

    thread NNNN panic: load of misaligned address 0x... for type
    'const unsigned int *', which requires 4 byte alignment
      lib/gx/command_processor.cpp:120 in unaligned_load<unsigned int>
      lib/gx/command_processor.cpp:134 in read_u32
      lib/gx/command_processor.cpp:392 in fifo::process
      lib/gx/fifo.cpp:75 in fifo::drain
      lib/aurora.cpp:251 in end_frame / aurora_end_frame

Root cause: the non-MSVC branch of `unaligned_load` reads a genuinely
unaligned GX FIFO command-stream pointer via the standard "memcpy into a
local" type-punning idiom, but its parameter was typed `const T*`:

    template <typename T>
    inline T unaligned_load(const T* ptr) {
      T copy;
      memcpy(&copy, ptr, sizeof(T));
      return copy;
    }
    ...
    const u32 val = unaligned_load(reinterpret_cast<const u32*>(ptr));

A `const T*` parameter still carries T's alignment requirement in the C++
abstract machine, independent of the fact that memcpy's own ABI doesn't
care about source alignment: forming `reinterpret_cast<const u32*>(ptr)`
from a `ptr` that isn't actually 4-byte aligned is already
implementation-defined/UB territory, and an optimizer is entitled to lower
`memcpy(&copy, ptr, 4)` straight to `load i32, ptr %ptr, align 4` on the
strength of that assumption. Real hardware (x86/x64) tolerates the
resulting unaligned load fine, but zig cc's LLVM backend instruments/traps
on it. This is a latent, portability-landmine bug in Aurora's own
"portable" (non-MSVC) fallback -- the MSVC branch sidesteps it entirely via
the `__unaligned` compiler extension, which is presumably why it was never
noticed there.

Fix: change `unaligned_load`'s parameter (both the MSVC and non-MSVC
branches, for a consistent signature) from `const T*` to `const void*`, and
update the two call sites (`read_u16`, `read_u32`) to stop forming a typed,
possibly-misaligned pointer before calling it -- pass the already-`const
u8*` pointer straight through and specify T explicitly as the template
argument instead. `void*` carries no alignment assumption, so the
optimizer can no longer "prove" 4-byte alignment and silently upgrade the
memcpy into a trapping aligned load.

--- a/lib/gx/command_processor.cpp
+++ b/lib/gx/command_processor.cpp
@@ -108,19 +108,31 @@

 // Read helpers for big/little endian
 #if _MSC_VER
 template <typename T>
 __forceinline // Yes, this was necessary.
-    inline T unaligned_load(const T* ptr) {
+    inline T unaligned_load(const void* ptr) {
   return *static_cast<const __unaligned T*>(ptr);
 }
 #else
+// NOTE(mp6-native/aurora-patches): templated on T but deliberately takes a
+// `const void*`, not `const T*`. A `const T*` parameter still carries T's
+// alignment requirement in the abstract machine even though memcpy itself
+// doesn't care about the source's alignment -- an optimizer is entitled to
+// (and, under zig cc's LLVM backend, does) lower this memcpy into a plain
+// `load ..., align sizeof(T)` and trap on the genuinely-unaligned FIFO
+// command-stream pointers this is called with. Confirmed via direct repro:
+// zig-cc-built aurora crashed with "panic: load of misaligned address ...
+// which requires 4 byte alignment" inside this function on the very first
+// aurora_end_frame()/fifo::drain() call. Taking `const void*` removes the
+// alignment assumption at its source instead of only hiding it one call
+// deeper (the call sites below also stopped forming a typed, possibly-
+// misaligned `const T*` at all, for the same reason).
 template <typename T>
-inline T unaligned_load(const T* ptr) {
+inline T unaligned_load(const void* ptr) {
   T copy;
   memcpy(&copy, ptr, sizeof(T));
   return copy;
 }
 #endif

 static inline u16 read_u16(const u8* ptr, bool bigEndian) {
-  const u16 val = unaligned_load(reinterpret_cast<const u16*>(ptr));
+  const u16 val = unaligned_load<u16>(ptr);
   if (bigEndian) {
     return bswap(val);
   }
   return val;
 }

 static inline u32 read_u32(const u8* ptr, bool bigEndian) {
-  const u32 val = unaligned_load(reinterpret_cast<const u32*>(ptr));
+  const u32 val = unaligned_load<u32>(ptr);
   if (bigEndian) {
     return bswap(val);
   }
   return val;
 }

Verified: after this change, both the zig-cc (x86_64-windows-gnu) build and
the MSVC (Visual Studio 17 2022) build of `simple` compile clean and run;
the zig-cc build no longer panics in fifo::drain() on the first frame.
